\ Regression via the loadable statistics library (lib/statistics.h2o):
\ LAPACKE dgelsd OLS and Firth-penalized logistic, with non-parametric
\ bootstrap inference. Native-only (FFI); the wasm suite skips it.
"lib/statistics.h2o" load

\ ===== linear regression (LAPACKE dgelsd) + non-parametric bootstrap inference =====

\ fit-linear recovers an exact line y = 2x + 1: beta = [intercept; slope] = [1; 2]
[ 1 1  1 2  1 3 ] 3 2 matrix  [ 3 5 7 ] 3 1 matrix  fit-linear . cr

\ regress: synthetic near-linear y ~ 2x + 1. point estimates are deterministic;
\ the bootstrap SE/CI are deterministic too under a fixed seed.
7 seed
[ [ "x" "y" ]
  [ 1 3.1 ] [ 2 4.9 ] [ 3 7.2 ] [ 4 8.8 ] [ 5 11.1 ] [ 6 12.9 ] ] 1 rows>dataset
[ :x ] :y 300 linear-regression . cr   \ intercept ~1, slope ~2, CIs bracketing them

\ regress on iris: petal_width ~ petal_length reproduces the textbook OLS,
\ slope ~0.4158, intercept ~-0.3631, with bootstrap SE/CI from resampling
7 seed
"data/iris.tsv" read-tsv 1 rows>dataset
[ :petal_length ] :petal_width 500 linear-regression . cr

\ ===== logistic regression (IRLS over dgelsd) =====

\ fit-logistic (Firth-penalized) on non-separable data: positive slope
[ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] 8 1 matrix with-intercept
[ 0 0 1 0 1 0 1 1 ] 8 1 matrix  25 1e-8 fit-logistic . cr

\ a tighter budget reaches the same fit
[ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] 8 1 matrix with-intercept
[ 0 0 1 0 1 0 1 1 ] 8 1 matrix  100 1e-10 fit-logistic . cr

\ the Firth penalty keeps the estimate finite even under perfect separation
\ (plain MLE would diverge to +/- infinity)
[ 1 2 3 4 ] 4 1 matrix with-intercept
[ 0 0 1 1 ] 4 1 matrix  25 1e-8 fit-logistic . cr

\ ridge logistic: lambda 0 is the plain MLE (no Firth); a huge lambda crushes
\ the slope toward 0 while the unpenalized intercept stays free
[ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] 8 1 matrix with-intercept
[ 0 0 1 0 1 0 1 1 ] 8 1 matrix  50 1e-8 0 fit-logistic-ridge . cr
[ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] 8 1 matrix with-intercept
[ 0 0 1 0 1 0 1 1 ] 8 1 matrix  50 1e-8 1000 fit-logistic-ridge . cr

\ ridge CV over a lambda grid: same folds for every lambda; the parallel
\ variant is result-identical by construction (deterministic cells)
[ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] 8 1 matrix to cv-X
[ 0 0 1 0 1 0 1 1 ] 8 1 matrix to cv-y
7 seed 8 iota shuffle to cv-units
cv-X cv-y cv-units [ 1 100 ] 2 cv-logistic-ridge to cv-serial
cv-serial . cr
cv-serial  cv-X cv-y cv-units [ 1 100 ] 2 pcv-logistic-ridge  = . cr   \ 1

\ dataset-level logistic-regression: iris virginica-vs-versicolor by sepal length,
\ the classic non-separable logistic. Bootstrap gives SE/CI/bias per coefficient;
\ Firth keeps every resample finite so the bootstrap never diverges.
"data/iris.tsv" read-tsv 1 rows>dataset :sepal_length @ 50 skip to sepal-lengths
0 50 array-of  1 50 array-of  concat to species-y
[ :sepal_length :y ]  sepal-lengths species-y 2 array  frame to iris-two
7 seed
iris-two [ :sepal_length ] :y 300 logistic-regression . cr   \ slope ~1.9
